  ],
  additional: [
    [
      `At ${page.annualFormatted}, your salary is ${percentOfMedian}% of the UK median. With zero personal allowance and income taxed at 20%, 40%, and 45%, your effective rate is ${page.englandFormatted.effectiveTaxRate}. Your monthly take-home of ${page.englandFormatted.netMonthly} is still substantial.`,
      `Housing budget at 30% of net: ${rentBudget30}/month. Mortgage capacity at 4.5x: ${mortgageMax}. At this income level, property ownership is accessible across the UK, including London.`,
      `Tax efficiency at the additional rate requires sophisticated planning. Pension contributions save at 45%, ISAs shelter £20,000/year, and venture capital trusts offer 30% income tax relief. Professional financial advice typically pays for itself many times over at this salary level.`,
    ],
    [
      `Earning ${page.annualFormatted} per year places you well into the additional rate band. At ${percentOfMedian}% of the UK median, your income is in the top tier of UK earners. Your take-home of ${page.englandFormatted.netMonthly}/month reflects deductions of ${page.englandFormatted.totalDeductions}.`,
      `Your housing budget under the 30% rule is ${rentBudget30}. With mortgage capacity of ${mortgageMax}, most of the UK property market is accessible. The focus at this level is wealth building and tax-efficient investment.`,
      `At 45% marginal tax, pension contributions are especially valuable. Every £100 in salary sacrifice saves £45 in income tax plus NI. Maximising your annual allowance (£60,000 or more with carry-forward) is one of the most effective strategies available.`,
    ],
    [
      `A salary of ${page.annualFormatted} is ${percentOfMedian}% of the national median. Your total deductions of ${page.englandFormatted.totalDeductions} leave you with ${page.englandFormatted.netMonthly} per month. At the additional rate, every financial decision carries tax implications worth considering.`,
      `With ${rentBudget30}/month for housing (30% rule) and mortgage capacity of ${mortgageMax}, your accommodation options are extensive. Financial planning at this income typically focuses on investment diversification and tax efficiency rather than basic affordability.`,
      `Key strategies at this rate: maximise pension contributions (£60,000 annual allowance with potential carry-forward), use ISA wrappers for investments, consider venture capital trusts and enterprise investment schemes, and review whether incorporation might be beneficial if you have self-employed income alongside your salary.`,
    ],
  ],
};

const contextParas = (contextVariants[page.tier] ?? contextVariants['basic'])[vIdx % (contextVariants[page.tier]?.length ?? 3)];
---

<html lang="en-GB">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
  <title>{metaTitle}</title>
  <meta name="description" content={description} />
  <meta name="author" content="Mottalib Radif" />
  <link rel="canonical" href={canonical} />
  <meta property="og:type" content="article" />
  <meta property="og:title" content={title} />
  <meta property="og:description" content={description} />
  <meta property="og:url" content={canonical} />
  <meta property="og:site_name" content={SITE_NAME} />
  <meta property="og:locale" content="en_GB" />
  <meta property="og:image" content={OG_IMAGE} />
  <meta property="og:image:width" content={OG_IMAGE_WIDTH} />
  <meta property="og:image:height" content={OG_IMAGE_HEIGHT} />
  <meta property="og:image:alt" content={`£${annualF} a year after tax UK - salary breakdown`} />
  <meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image" />
  <meta name="twitter:title" content={title} />
  <meta name="twitter:description" content={description} />
  <meta name="twitter:image" content={OG_IMAGE} />
  <BaseHead slug={`/salary/${page.slug}/`} pageType="salary" />
  <link rel="icon" type="image/svg+xml" href="/favicon.svg" />
  <link rel="icon" type="image/x-icon" href="/favicon.ico" />
  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="en-GB" href={canonical} />
  <link rel="preload" href="/fonts/inter-400.woff2" as="font" type="font/woff2" crossorigin />
  <link rel="preload" href="/fonts/inter-700.woff2" as="font" type="font/woff2" crossorigin />
  <link rel="manifest" href="/manifest.webmanifest" />
  {schemas.map((schema) => (
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schema)} />
  ))}
</head>
<body class="min-h-screen bg-white text-gray-900 dark:bg-gray-950 dark:text-gray-100">
  <a href="#main-content" class="skip-link bg-navy-600 text-white">Skip to content</a>
  <Header />

  <main id="main-content" class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-8 sm:px-6 sm:py-12">
    <Breadcrumbs items={breadcrumbItems} />
    <article class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none">

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- 1. H1 + Intro -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <h1>£{annualF} a Year After Tax: UK Take-Home Pay Breakdown</h1>
      <p set:html={introHtml} />

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- 2. Summary Results Table -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <h2>Your {page.annualFormatted} Salary at a Glance</h2>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Item</th>
              <th class="text-right">Annual</th>
              <th class="text-right">Monthly</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Gross salary</td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{page.englandFormatted.grossAnnual}</td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{page.englandFormatted.grossMonthly}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Income tax</td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{page.englandFormatted.incomeTax}</td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{formatCurrency(page.england.incomeTax / 12)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>National Insurance</td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{page.englandFormatted.nationalInsurance}</td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{formatCurrency(page.england.nationalInsurance / 12)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Total deductions</strong></td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums"><strong>{page.englandFormatted.totalDeductions}</strong></td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums"><strong>{formatCurrency(page.england.totalDeductions / 12)}</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-accent-50 dark:bg-accent-500/10">
              <td><strong>Take-home pay</strong></td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums"><strong>{page.englandFormatted.netAnnual}</strong></td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums"><strong>{page.englandFormatted.netMonthly}</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Effective tax rate</td>
              <td class="text-right" colspan="2">{page.englandFormatted.effectiveTaxRate}</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- 3. CTA Button -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <div class="not-prose my-8 text-center">
        <a
          href="/"
          data-gross={page.annual}
          class="cta-calc inline-block rounded-lg bg-navy-600 px-6 py-3 text-lg font-semibold text-white shadow-md transition-colors hover:bg-navy-700 focus-visible:outline focus-visible:outline-2 focus-visible:outline-offset-2 focus-visible:outline-navy-600"
        >
          Calculate your exact take-home pay &rarr;
        </a>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- 4. How Your Salary Is Taxed -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <h2>How Your {page.annualFormatted} Salary Is Taxed</h2>

      {page.tier === 'below-pa' ? (
        <>
          <p>
            Your annual salary of {page.annualFormatted} falls entirely within the <strong>Personal Allowance</strong>,
            which is the amount you can earn tax-free each year. For the {TAX_YEAR} tax year, the Personal Allowance
            is <strong>{formatCurrency(PERSONAL_ALLOWANCE)}</strong>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Since {page.annualFormatted} is less than {formatCurrency(PERSONAL_ALLOWANCE)}, your entire income is
            covered by the Personal Allowance. This means:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Income tax: {page.englandFormatted.incomeTax}</strong> — no tax is due because your salary is below the tax-free threshold.</li>
            {paysNI ? (
              <li>
                <strong>National Insurance: {page.englandFormatted.nationalInsurance} per year</strong> —
                you still pay NI because your earnings above the NI threshold ({formatCurrency(NI_PRIMARY_THRESHOLD)}/year)
                are subject to the 8% rate.
              </li>
            ) : (
              <li>
                <strong>National Insurance: {page.englandFormatted.nationalInsurance}</strong> —
                your salary is also below the NI Primary Threshold of {formatCurrency(NI_PRIMARY_THRESHOLD)}/year,
                so no NI is due either.
              </li>
            )}
          </ul>
        </>
      ) : page.tier === 'basic' ? (
        <>
          <p>
            The UK uses a <strong>progressive tax system</strong>, meaning different portions of your income are taxed
            at different rates. Here is how your {page.annualFormatted} annual salary is broken down step by step:
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <strong>Personal Allowance ({formatCurrency(PERSONAL_ALLOWANCE)}):</strong> The first {formatCurrency(PERSONAL_ALLOWANCE)} of your
              income is tax-free. This is your Personal Allowance for {TAX_YEAR}.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Basic Rate at 20%:</strong> Income above the Personal Allowance up to £50,270 is taxed at 20%.
              For your salary, {formatCurrency(taxableIncome)} is taxed at the basic rate, producing
              {page.englandFormatted.incomeTax} in income tax.
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            Your total income tax for the year is <strong>{page.englandFormatted.incomeTax}</strong>,
            or {formatCurrency(page.england.incomeTax / 12)} per month.
          </p>
        </>
      ) : page.tier === 'higher' ? (
        <>
          <p>
            At {page.annualFormatted}, your salary spans two taxable bands. The UK tax system is progressive, so each
            portion is taxed at its own rate:
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <strong>Personal Allowance ({formatCurrency(PERSONAL_ALLOWANCE)}):</strong> The first {formatCurrency(PERSONAL_ALLOWANCE)} is
              completely tax-free.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Basic Rate at 20%:</strong> Income from {formatCurrency(PERSONAL_ALLOWANCE)} to £50,270
              ({formatCurrency(50270 - PERSONAL_ALLOWANCE)}) is taxed at 20%.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Higher Rate at 40%:</strong> Income from £50,270 to {page.annualFormatted}
              ({formatCurrency(page.annual - 50270)}) is taxed at 40%.
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            Your total income tax is <strong>{page.englandFormatted.incomeTax}</strong> ({formatCurrency(page.england.incomeTax / 12)}/month).
            Your marginal rate is {page.englandFormatted.marginalTaxRate}, meaning each additional pound earned is
            taxed at this rate.
          </p>
        </>
      ) : page.tier === 'taper' ? (
        <>
          <p>
            At {page.annualFormatted}, you are in the <strong>personal allowance taper zone</strong> (£100,000 to £125,140).
            Your Personal Allowance is reduced by £1 for every £2 you earn above £100,000. This creates an effective
            <strong> 60% marginal tax rate</strong> within this band — one of the highest rates in the UK tax system.
          </p>
          <p>
            Your reduced Personal Allowance is <strong>{formatCurrency(page.england.personalAllowance)}</strong>
            (down from {formatCurrency(PERSONAL_ALLOWANCE)}). Here is how the tax is calculated:
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <strong>Reduced Personal Allowance ({formatCurrency(page.england.personalAllowance)}):</strong> Only this amount is
              tax-free, due to the taper.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Basic Rate at 20%:</strong> Income from {formatCurrency(page.england.personalAllowance)} to £50,270.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Higher Rate at 40%:</strong> Income from £50,270 to {page.annualFormatted}.
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            Your total income tax is <strong>{page.englandFormatted.incomeTax}</strong>. The effective 60% marginal
            rate means that for every £100 you earn in the taper zone, you lose £60 to tax (£40 at the higher rate
            plus £20 from the reduced allowance being taxed at 40%).
          </p>
        </>
      ) : (
        <>
          <p>
            At {page.annualFormatted}, you are an additional rate taxpayer. Your Personal Allowance has been fully
            tapered to <strong>£0</strong> (it reduces to zero for incomes above £125,140). Your salary is taxed
            across three bands:
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <strong>Basic Rate at 20%:</strong> The first £37,700 of taxable income (up to £50,270) is taxed at 20%.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Higher Rate at 40%:</strong> Income from £50,270 to £125,140 ({formatCurrency(125140 - 50270)}) is
              taxed at 40%.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Additional Rate at 45%:</strong> Income above £125,140
              ({formatCurrency(page.annual - 125140)}) is taxed at 45%.
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            Your total income tax is <strong>{page.englandFormatted.incomeTax}</strong>
            ({formatCurrency(page.england.incomeTax / 12)}/month). With no Personal Allowance, every pound
            you earn is subject to tax. Your marginal rate is {page.englandFormatted.marginalTaxRate}.
          </p>
        </>
      )}

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- 5. Band-by-Band Table -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      {page.englandFormatted.bands.length > 0 && (
        <>
          <h2>Income Tax Band-by-Band Breakdown</h2>
          <p>
            The table below shows exactly how much of your {page.annualFormatted} salary falls in each income tax
            band for England, Wales, and Northern Ireland in {TAX_YEAR}:
          </p>
          <div class="overflow-x-auto">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Tax Band</th>
                  <th class="text-right">Rate</th>
                  <th class="text-right">Taxable Amount</th>
                  <th class="text-right">Tax</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>Personal Allowance</td>
                  <td class="text-right">0%</td>
                  <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{formatCurrency(page.england.personalAllowance)}</td>
                  <td class="text-right tabular-nums">£0</td>
                </tr>
                {page.englandFormatted.bands.map((band) => (
                  <tr>
                    <td>{band.name}</td>
                    <td class="text-right">{(band.rate * 100).toFixed(0)}%</td>
                    <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{formatCurrency(band.taxableAmount)}</td>
                    <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{formatCurrency(band.tax)}</td>
                  </tr>
                ))}
                <tr class="font-semibold">
                  <td>Total</td>
                  <td class="text-right"></td>
                  <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{page.englandFormatted.grossAnnual}</td>
                  <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{page.englandFormatted.incomeTax}</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </>
      )}

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- 6. National Insurance -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <h2>National Insurance on {page.annualFormatted}</h2>
      {paysNI ? (
        <>
          <p>
            National Insurance Contributions (NICs) are calculated separately from income tax. For employees in
            the {TAX_YEAR} tax year, Class 1 NICs are charged at:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>8%</strong> on earnings between {formatCurrency(NI_PRIMARY_THRESHOLD)} and {formatCurrency(NI_UPPER_EARNINGS_LIMIT)} per year</li>
            <li><strong>2%</strong> on earnings above {formatCurrency(NI_UPPER_EARNINGS_LIMIT)} per year</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            On your annual salary of {page.annualFormatted}, your total NI for the year is
            <strong> {page.englandFormatted.nationalInsurance}</strong>, or approximately
            {formatCurrency(page.england.nationalInsurance / 12)} per month.
          </p>
        </>
      ) : (
        <>
          <p>
            National Insurance Contributions (NICs) for employees are charged on earnings above the Primary Threshold,
            which is {formatCurrency(NI_PRIMARY_THRESHOLD)} per year for {TAX_YEAR}. Since your annual salary of
            {page.annualFormatted} is at or below this threshold, <strong>you pay no National Insurance</strong>.
          </p>
          <p>
            However, you may still build up qualifying years for the State Pension if your earnings are above the
            Lower Earnings Limit of £6,708 per year ({page.annual >= 6708 ? 'which your salary exceeds' : 'which your salary is below'}).
          </p>
        </>
      )}

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- 7. Period Conversion Table -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <h2>What You Take Home Each Pay Period</h2>
      <p>
        Here is what {page.annualFormatted} per year looks like across different pay periods, showing both your
        gross (before-tax) and net (after-tax) amounts for England in {TAX_YEAR}:
      </p>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Period</th>
              <th class="text-right">Gross</th>
              <th class="text-right">Take-Home</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {page.periods.map((p) => (
              <tr>
                <td>{p.label}</td>
                <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{p.gross}</td>
                <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{p.net}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        At {page.annualFormatted} per year gross, your effective hourly rate is {page.hourlyGross} before tax
        (based on a 37.5-hour week), or approximately {formatCurrency(page.england.netAnnual / (52 * 37.5))} per
        hour after tax. Your daily take-home is roughly {formatCurrency(page.england.netAnnual / 365)}.
      </p>

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- 8. Scotland Comparison -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <h2>England vs Scotland: {page.annualFormatted} Per Year Comparison</h2>
      <p>
        Scotland has its own income tax rates that differ from England, Wales, and Northern Ireland. If you live in
        Scotland and earn {page.annualFormatted} per year, your take-home pay may differ. National Insurance rates
        are the same across the UK. Here is the comparison:
      </p>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Item</th>
              <th class="text-right">England</th>
              <th class="text-right">Scotland</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Gross annual</td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{page.englandFormatted.grossAnnual}</td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{page.scotlandFormatted.grossAnnual}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Income tax</td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{page.englandFormatted.incomeTax}</td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{page.scotlandFormatted.incomeTax}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>National Insurance</td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{page.englandFormatted.nationalInsurance}</td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{page.scotlandFormatted.nationalInsurance}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Total deductions</td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{page.englandFormatted.totalDeductions}</td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{page.scotlandFormatted.totalDeductions}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-accent-50 dark:bg-accent-500/10">
              <td><strong>Net annual</strong></td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums"><strong>{page.englandFormatted.netAnnual}</strong></td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums"><strong>{page.scotlandFormatted.netAnnual}</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-accent-50 dark:bg-accent-500/10">
              <td><strong>Net monthly</strong></td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums"><strong>{page.englandFormatted.netMonthly}</strong></td>
              <td class="text-right tabular-nums"><strong>{page.scotlandFormatted.netMonthly}</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Effective rate</td>
              <td class="text-right">{page.englandFormatted.effectiveTaxRate}</td>
              <td class="text-right">{page.scotlandFormatted.effectiveTaxRate}</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      {page.england.incomeTax !== page.scotland.incomeTax ? (
        <p>
          The difference in take-home pay between England and Scotland on {page.annualFormatted} per year
          is <strong>{formatCurrency(Math.abs(page.england.netAnnual - page.scotland.netAnnual))} per year</strong>
          ({formatCurrency(Math.abs(page.england.netAnnual - page.scotland.netAnnual) / 12)} per month).
          {page.england.netAnnual > page.scotland.netAnnual
            ? ' You take home more in England due to lower income tax rates at this level.'
            : ' You take home more in Scotland at this income level.'}
        </p>
      ) : (
        <p>
          At this salary level, income tax is the same in both England and Scotland ({page.englandFormatted.incomeTax}),
          so your take-home pay is identical regardless of where you live in the UK.
        </p>
      )}

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- 9. What This Salary Means -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <h2>What £{annualF} a Year Means in Practice</h2>
      {contextParas.map((para) => (
        <p>{para}</p>
      ))}

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- 10. Nearby Salary Comparisons -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <h2>Nearby Annual Salary Comparison</h2>
      <p>
        Wondering how a change in salary affects your take-home? The table below compares annual salaries
        near {page.annualFormatted}, showing the net annual and monthly pay and the difference from your current salary:
      </p>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Annual Salary</th>
              <th class="text-right">Net Annual</th>
              <th class="text-right">Net Monthly</th>
              <th class="text-right">vs {page.annualFormatted}</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {page.nearby.map((n) => (
              <tr>
                <td><a href={`/salary/${n.slug}/`} class="text-navy-600 hover:underline dark:text-navy-300">{n.annualFormatted}</a></td>
                <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{n.netAnnual}</td>
                <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{n.netMonthly}</td>
                <td class="text-right tabular-nums">{n.difference}/yr</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        As you can see, each increase in gross salary does not result in an equivalent increase in take-home
        pay. After income tax and National Insurance, you keep approximately
        {page.tier === 'basic' ? '72p' : page.tier === 'higher' ? '58p' : page.tier === 'taper' ? '40p' : page.tier === 'additional' ? '53p' : '92p'}
        of every additional £1 earned at your current marginal rate.
      </p>

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- 11. FAQs -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      {faqs.map((faq) => (
        <details class="group border-b border-gray-200 py-4 dark:border-gray-700">
          <summary class="cursor-pointer list-none font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
            <span class="flex items-center justify-between">
              {faq.question}
              <svg class="ml-2 h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
            </span>
          </summary>
          <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">{faq.answer}</p>
        </details>
      ))}

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- 12. Second CTA -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <div class="not-prose my-8 text-center">
        <a
          href="/"
          data-gross={page.annual}
          class="cta-calc inline-block rounded-lg bg-navy-600 px-6 py-3 text-lg font-semibold text-white shadow-md transition-colors hover:bg-navy-700 focus-visible:outline focus-visible:outline-2 focus-visible:outline-offset-2 focus-visible:outline-navy-600"
        >
          Try the full salary calculator &rarr;
        </a>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">
          Add student loans, pension, Scotland rates, and more.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- 13. Related Calculators -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <h2>Related Calculators</h2>
      <div class="not-prose grid grid-cols-1 gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
        <a href="/" class="rounded-lg border border-gray-200 p-4 transition-colors hover:border-navy-300 hover:bg-navy-50 dark:border-gray-700 dark:hover:border-navy-600 dark:hover:bg-navy-900/20">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy-700 dark:text-navy-300">Salary Calculator</h3>
          <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">Full UK salary calculator with all options.</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/take-home-pay/" class="rounded-lg border border-gray-200 p-4 transition-colors hover:border-navy-300 hover:bg-navy-50 dark:border-gray-700 dark:hover:border-navy-600 dark:hover:bg-navy-900/20">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy-700 dark:text-navy-300">Take-Home Pay</h3>
          <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">See your net pay after all deductions.</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/income-tax/" class="rounded-lg border border-gray-200 p-4 transition-colors hover:border-navy-300 hover:bg-navy-50 dark:border-gray-700 dark:hover:border-navy-600 dark:hover:bg-navy-900/20">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy-700 dark:text-navy-300">Income Tax Calculator</h3>
